<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>
  
<exercise xml:id="conv-mcq-1">
  <title>Definition of Convolution</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The convolution of two functions <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> (for <m>t \ge 0</m>) is defined as:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>(f * g)(t) = \int_{0}^{t} f(\tau)\, g(t-\tau)\, d\tau</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This is exactly the definition of convolution.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>(f * g)(t) = f(t)g(t)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—convolution is not pointwise multiplication.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>(f * g)(t) = \int_{0}^{\infty} f(\tau)g(\tau)\, d\tau</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this describes an inner product, not convolution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-mcq-2">
  <title>Understanding Example 3.3.1</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In <url href=" 
https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/convolution_section.html#example-61">Example 3.3.1</url>, the convolution of <m>f(t)=e^{t}</m> and <m>g(t)=t</m> is computed.  
      Which statement below is true about <m>(f * g)(t)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          It equals <m>e^{t}(t-1)</m> after evaluating the integral.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <url href="
https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/convolution_section.html#example-61">Example 3.3.1</url> shows that  
          <m>(f*g)(t)=\int_{0}^{t} e^{\tau}(t-\tau)\, d\tau = e^{t}(t-1)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>It equals <m>t\,e^{t}</m> with no subtraction.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—an integration by parts yields a <m>-e^{t}</m> correction term.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>It equals <m>t^{2}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—there is no polynomial result here.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-mcq-3">
  <title>Laplace Transform of a Convolution</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What does the Convolution Theorem state?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}\{f * g\}(s) = F(s)\,G(s)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The Laplace transform of a convolution is the product of the transforms.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}\{f * g\}(s) = F(s) + G(s)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the theorem involves multiplication, not addition.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>{\cal L}\{f * g\}(s) = \dfrac{F(s)}{G(s)}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—division does not appear in the convolution theorem.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-mcq-4">
  <title>Basic Properties of Convolution</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following is a true property of convolution?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>f * g = g * f</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Convolution is commutative.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>(f * g)(t) = f(t)</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this is false unless <m>g</m> is a delta function.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>f * (g+h) = (f*g) - (f*h)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—convolution distributes over addition with a plus, not a minus.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-mcq-5">
  <title>Using the Convolution Theorem</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      To compute
      <m>{\cal L}^{-1}\!\left\{\dfrac{1}{(s+1)s^{2}}\right\}</m>,
      we can recognize the expression as
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The product <m>\dfrac{1}{s+1}\cdot \dfrac{1}{s^{2}}</m>,  
          whose inverse transform is the convolution of <m>e^{-t}</m> and <m>t</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.   
          <m>{\cal L}^{-1}\{1/(s+1)s^{2}\} = (e^{-t} * t)(t)</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The sum of two transforms.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—it is a product of transforms.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>A quotient <m>\dfrac{1/s}{1/(s+1)}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—we do not use division for convolution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-purpose">
  <statement>
    <p>
      <url href="https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/convolution_section.html#theorem-15">Theorem 3.3.1</url>
      sheds light on why we care to bother defining the convolution.
      In your own words, describe the purpose of defining a convolution product.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The convolution is defined so that its Laplace transform becomes the
      <em>product</em> of the Laplace transforms of the original functions.
      In other words,
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}\{(f * g)(t)\} = F(s)\,G(s),
    </me>

    <p>
      which is <url href="
https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/convolution_section.html#theorem-15">Theorem 3.3.1</url>.  This is extremely useful because it lets us take 
      an inverse Laplace transform of a product by converting that product 
      into a convolution integral of simpler functions whose inverse transforms we already know.  
      The convolution therefore provides a way to solve differential equations and compute
      inverse transforms that would be very difficult otherwise. 
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-ft2-ut1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(t)=t^{2}</m> for <m>t\ge 0</m> and <m>g(t)=u(t-1)</m>.
      Compute the convolution product <m>(f * g)(t)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      By definition of convolution,  
    </p>

    <me>
      (f * g)(t)
      = \int_{0}^{t} f(\tau)\, g(t-\tau)\, d\tau
      = \int_{0}^{t} \tau^{2}\, u(t-\tau-1)\, d\tau.  
    </me>

    <p>
      The factor <m>u(t-\tau-1)</m> equals 1 exactly when 
      <m>t - \tau \ge 1</m>, i.e. <m>\tau \le t-1</m>.  
      Therefore the integral becomes:
    </p>

    <me>
      (f * g)(t)
      = \int_{0}^{t-1} \tau^{2}\, d\tau
      \quad \text{for } t \ge 1,\qquad
      (f * g)(t) = 0 \text{ for } t &lt; 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the integral:
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{t-1} \tau^{2}\, d\tau
      = \left. \frac{\tau^{3}}{3} \right|_{0}^{\,t-1}
      = \frac{(t-1)^{3}}{3}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      (f * g)(t) =
      \begin{cases}
         0, \amp t &lt; 1,\\[6pt]
         \dfrac{(t-1)^{3}}{3}, \amp t \ge 1.
      \end{cases}
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="conv-volterra">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the Volterra integral equation
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t) = e^{-t} + \int_{0}^{t} \cos(t-\tau)\, x(\tau)\, d\tau.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Apply the Laplace transform.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Let <m>X(s)={\cal L}\{x(t)\}</m>.  
      Using the convolution theorem:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}\!\left[\int_{0}^{t} \cos(t-\tau)x(\tau)\,d\tau\right]
      =
      {\cal L}\{\cos t\}\, X(s)
      =
      \frac{s}{s^{2}+1} X(s).  
    </me>

    <p>
      Also <m>{\cal L}\{e^{-t}\} = \dfrac{1}{s+1}</m>.  
      Taking the Laplace transform of the entire equation gives
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s) = \frac{1}{s+1} + \frac{s}{s^{2}+1} X(s).
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Solve for <m>X(s)</m>.</strong></p>

    <me>
      X(s)\!\left(1 - \frac{s}{s^{2}+1}\right)
      = \frac{1}{s+1}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the factor:
    </p>

    <me>
      1 - \frac{s}{s^{2}+1}
      =
      \frac{s^{2}+1 - s}{s^{2}+1}
      =
      \frac{s^{2}-s+1}{s^{2}+1}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus:
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s)
      = \frac{1}{s+1}\,\frac{s^{2}+1}{\,s^{2}-s+1\,}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>3. Invert the transform.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Rewrite <m>s^{2}+1</m> to match the denominator:
    </p>

    <me>
      s^{2}+1
      = (s^{2}-s+1) + s.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore:
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s)
      = \frac{1}{s+1}
        \left(
          1 + \frac{s}{s^{2}-s+1}
        \right)
      = \frac{1}{s+1}
        + \frac{s}{(s+1)(s^{2}-s+1)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The inverse Laplace transform of <m>1/(s+1)</m> is <m>e^{-t}</m>.
    </p>

    <p><strong>4. Invert the second term.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Note that  
      <m>s^{2}-s+1 = (s-\tfrac12)^{2} + \tfrac34</m>.  
      Thus the denominator corresponds to a damped sinusoid:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{s-\frac12}{(s-\frac12)^{2} + (\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})^{2}}\right]
      = e^{t/2}\cos\!\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}t\right),
    </me>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{(s-\frac12)^{2} + (\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})^{2}}\right]
      = e^{t/2}\sin\!\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}t\right).
    </me>

    <p>
      Carefully decomposing the fraction and inverting gives the final solution:
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      =
      e^{-t}
      \;+\;
      \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\,e^{-t/2}\,
      \sin\!\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}t\right).
    </me>

    <p>
      One may check directly (by differentiating and substituting) that this function satisfies the original integral equation.
    </p>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives33">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
Use the convolution theorem <m>\mathcal{L}\{f*g\} = \mathcal{L}\{f\}\mathcal{L}\{g\}</m> to compute inverse Laplace transforms.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Apply convolution to solve linear ODEs with general forcing functions expressed through Laplace transforms.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Decompose rational expressions into Laplace-transformable factors and interpret solutions as convolutions of known functions.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>